Your GHK-Cu Injection Comfort Guide
Simple tips to make your injections easier and less painful. This guide
explains why you might feel some sting—and what you can do about it.

UNDERSTANDING YOUR INJECTION

Why Does It Sting?
A little pain is normal with GHK-Cu. Here''s why it happens—and it''s not the
saline.

1

The Copper
GHK-Cu has copper in it. Copper can bug your skin a little when it goes under
it. This is the main reason you feel a sting.

2

How Fast You Push


If you push the medicine in too fast, it stretches your skin quickly. That stretch
causes pain. Going slow helps a lot.

3

Where You Inject
Some spots on your body have more nerves than others. If you hit a nerve, it
will sting more. Moving to a new spot can help.

BEFORE YOUR SHOT

Get Ready the Right Way
A few simple steps before you inject can make a big difference in how it
feels.

1

Warm It Up
Take your medicine out of the fridge and let it sit for a few minutes. Cold
medicine hurts more. Room temperature is better.

2

Press on the Spot First
Use your thumb to press on the spot where you''ll inject. Hold it there for about
10 seconds. This can make the shot hurt less.


3

Use a Small Needle
Smaller needles hurt less. Ask us about using a short, thin needle if you don''t
already have one.

4

Try Ice (Optional)
Some people like to put ice on the spot for a minute first. This numbs the skin a
bit. Try it and see if it helps you.

DURING YOUR SHOT

The Right Way to Inject
Good technique makes a real difference. Follow these steps for a smoother
injection.

1

Go In Smooth
Don''t jab the needle in. Push it through your skin in one smooth move. Quick
and steady is best.

2

Push Slowly
This is the most important tip. Push the plunger very slowly. Give your skin
time to accept the medicine. Rushing causes more pain.


Don''t Pull Back First

3

You don''t need to pull back on the plunger before you push. This old trick
doesn''t help and can hurt more.

AFTER YOUR SHOT

Finishing Up
What to do right after you inject to help everything go smoothly.

Right After
✓

Count to 10 before taking the needle out

✓

This lets the medicine spread out

✓

It also stops leaking

✓

Press gently on the spot—don''t rub

For Next Time
✓

Use a different spot each time

✓

Keep spots at least an inch apart

✓

Your belly usually works best


Write down where you inject to help you rotate

✓

A Little Bruising Is OK
Small bruises or a tiny bit of blood at the spot is normal. It doesn''t mean
anything went wrong, and your body will still absorb the medicine just fine.

STILL HAVING PAIN?

Extra Things to Try
If your shots still hurt after trying everything above, here are a few more
ideas.

1

Change Your Spot
Try areas with more fat, like your belly. Arms and thighs can be more sensitive.
Find what works best for your body.

2

Relax Your Muscles


Tense muscles make shots hurt more. Take a deep breath and let your body
relax before you inject. It really helps.

3

Give It Time
Your body often gets used to injections after a few times. Many people say the
first few are the worst, then it gets easier.

IMPORTANT

When to Call Us
Most injection pain goes away in a few minutes. But reach out if you notice
any of these things.

Call or Text Us If:
✓

Pain lasts more than an hour

✓

The area gets very red or swollen

✓

You see signs of infection (pus, hot skin, fever)

✓

You''re worried about anything at all


This Is Normal:
✓

A sting that goes away in a few minutes

✓

Small bruise at the spot

✓

Tiny bit of blood

✓

Slight redness that fades quickly

We''re here to help. If you have questions or need to adjust your protocol,
just reach out.

